Welcome back to The Daily Courant, your afternoon banquet of Puck=E2=80=99s
freshest reporting.

=C2=A0

First up today, Eriq Gardner chronicles a development that might spoil Chri=
stmas in Hollywood: fears that Harmeet Dhillon, the president-elect=E2=80=
=99s choice to run the D.O.J. Civil Rights Division, could use the agency=
=E2=80=99s power to scrutinize what Republicans call reverse racism at ente=
rtainment companies like Disney, which have D.E.I. policies, or
even the Academy, which has added =E2=80=9Cinclusion standards=E2=80=9D to =
be eligible for the best picture Oscar.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Plus, below the fold: Peter Hamby has exclusive polling data revealing how =
Americans actually feel about Elon and Vivek=E2=80=99s DOGE experiment. Mar=
ion Maneker gets a download on the fast-rising textile designer and painter
Melissa Joseph from a couple art world insiders. And Baratunde Thurston con=
nects with Bill Cohan, in a conversation presented by Meta, to explore how =
Wall Street is countenancing the rise of artificial intelligence.

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, on the pods=E2=80=A6 John Ourand rings up ESPN=E2=80=99s Seth Wi=
ckersham to assess the media impact of Bill
Belichick=E2=80=99s jump to UNC. On The Town, Matt Belloni is joined by CMG=
 Worldwide founder Mark Roesler to consider the afterlife of a deceased art=
ist=E2=80=99s rights. On Impolitic, John Heilemann and former Obama advisor=
 Dan Pfeiffer offer a fresh perspective on the Dems=E2=80=99 soul-searching=
 walkabout. And on The Powers That Be, Bill Cohan regales Peter with incisi=
ve analysis of
